<body>
    <h1>Introduction to Computer Systems</h1>
    <div class=3D"Section1">
        <ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>Introduction to computations</p></li>
<li>
<p>Early history of computing devices;</p></li>
<li>
<p>Computers;</p></li>
<li>
<p>Major components of a computer; Hardware: processor, memory, I/O devices=
 </p></li>
<li>
<p>Software: Operating system, application software</p></li>
<li>
<p>Basic architecture of a computer</p></li>
<li>
<p>Basic Information Technology</p></li>
<li>
<p>The Internet</p></li>
<li>
<p>Number system: binary, octal, hexadecimal, binary arithmetic</p></li>
</ol>
<p></p>
<p></p>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>Introduction to computations</p></li>
</ol>
<p>Here=E2=80=99s a <strong>clear introduction to computations</strong> fro=
m a fundamental perspective:</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-1=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3WhatisComputatio=
n?">1=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 What is Computation?</h2>
<p><strong>Computation</strong> is the process of solving problems, perform=
ing calculations, or processing information using a <strong>well-defined se=
t of rules or instructions</strong>.</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Essentially, it=E2=80=99s <strong>transforming input into output</strong=
> using a method or algorithm.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Can be done by <strong>humans, machines, or both</strong>.</p></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Examples:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Adding two numbers (2 + 3 =E2=86=92 5)</p></li>
<li>
<p>Sorting a list of names alphabetically</p></li>
<li>
<p>Searching for a word in a document</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-2=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3KeyComponentsofC=
omputation">2=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Key Components of Computation</h2>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p><strong>Input</strong> =E2=80=93 The data provided to the computation.</=
p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Process</strong> =E2=80=93 The set of operations, rules, or algo=
rithms applied to the input.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Output</strong> =E2=80=93 The result produced by the computation=
.</p></li>
</ol>
<p><strong>Formulaically:</strong></p>
<p>Computation:Input=E2=86=92AlgorithmOutput\text{Computation} : \text{Inpu=
t} \xrightarrow{\text{Algorithm}} \text{Output}</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-3=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3TypesofComputati=
on">3=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Types of Computation</h2>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p><strong>Exact Computation</strong> =E2=80=93 Produces precise, determini=
stic results.</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Example: Calculating 5 =C3=97 7 =3D 35</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Approximate Computation</strong> =E2=80=93 Produces results clos=
e to the exact value, useful for complex or large problems.</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Example: Numerical solutions to differential equations</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Symbolic Computation</strong> =E2=80=93 Manipulates symbols or e=
xpressions rather than numbers.</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Example: Simplifying algebraic expressions</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Logical/Boolean Computation</strong> =E2=80=93 Uses true/false o=
r yes/no values.</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Example: Decision-making in algorithms</p></li>
</ul></li>
</ol>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-4=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3ModelsofComputat=
ion">4=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Models of Computation</h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Turing Machine</strong> =E2=80=93 Abstract model defining what p=
roblems are computable.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Finite Automata</strong> =E2=80=93 Computation with limited memo=
ry, used in pattern recognition.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Lambda Calculus</strong> =E2=80=93 Mathematical model for defini=
ng functions and transformations.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-5=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3WhyComputationis=
Important">5=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Why Computation is Important</h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Problem Solving:</strong> Enables systematic solutions to comple=
x tasks.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Automation:</strong> Computers perform repetitive tasks faster t=
han humans.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Scientific Modeling:</strong> Simulates real-world phenomena (we=
ather, physics, biology).</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Decision Making:</strong> Helps in AI, business analytics, and e=
ngineering.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<p>=F0=9F=92=A1 <strong>Key Idea:</strong><br>
At its core, computation is <strong>input + algorithm =E2=86=92 output</str=
ong>. Understanding this foundation is critical before diving into programm=
ing, algorithms, or computational theory.</p>
<hr>
<p>If you want, I can also explain <strong>=E2=80=9Ctypes of computational =
problems and complexity=E2=80=9D</strong> next, which is the natural contin=
uation of this topic. Do you want me to do that?</p>
<p></p>
<ol start=3D"2">
<li>
<p>Early history of computing devices;</p></li>
</ol>
<p>Here=E2=80=99s a <strong>structured overview of the early history of com=
puting devices</strong>, from simple tools to mechanical computers:</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-1=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3Prehistoric&amp;=
AncientTools">1=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Prehistoric &amp; Ancient Tools</h2>
<p><strong>a) Counting Tools (Pre-3000 BCE)</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Tally sticks:</strong> Marking notches to count objects.</p></li=
>
<li>
<p><strong>Quipus (Inca):</strong> Knotted strings for numerical recording.=
</p></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>b) Abacus (c. 2400 BCE =E2=80=93 China, Mesopotamia, Egypt)</str=
ong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Early <strong>mechanical aid</strong> for arithmetic.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Uses beads on rods to represent numbers.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Still used in some regions today for quick calculations.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-2=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3MechanicalComput=
ation">2=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Mechanical Computation</h2>
<p><strong>a) Antikythera Mechanism (c. 100 BCE, Greece)</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Earliest known <strong>analog mechanical device</strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Calculated positions of celestial bodies.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Precursor to clocks and astronomical calculators.</p></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>b) Napier=E2=80=99s Bones (1617, John Napier)</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Multiplication and division using rods marked with numbers.</p></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>c) Slide Rule (1620s, William Oughtred)</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Based on <strong>logarithms</strong> to perform multiplication, division=
, and powers.</p></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>d) Pascaline (1642, Blaise Pascal)</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Mechanical adding machine</strong> using gears.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Could add and subtract directly; multiplication/division done through re=
peated addition/subtraction.</p></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>e) Leibniz=E2=80=99s Step Reckoner (1673)</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Advanced Pascaline with ability to multiply, divide, and calculate roots=
.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-3=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3Early19thCentury=
=E2=80=93TheAnalyticalEngine">3=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Early 19th Century =E2=80=
=93 The Analytical Engine</h2>
<p><strong>Charles Babbage (1791=E2=80=931871)</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Difference Engine:</strong> Automatic calculation of polynomial =
tables.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Analytical Engine:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>First concept of a <strong>programmable mechanical computer</strong>.</p=
></li>
<li>
<p>Components similar to modern computers:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Input:</strong> Punched cards</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Processing:</strong> Arithmetic logic unit (ALU)</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Memory:</strong> Storage for numbers</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Output:</strong> Printed results</p></li>
</ul></li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Ada Lovelace</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Considered the <strong>first computer programmer</strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Wrote algorithms for the Analytical Engine.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-4=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3Late19th=E2=80=
=93Early20thCentury">4=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Late 19th =E2=80=93 Early 20th Cen=
tury</h2>
<p><strong>a) Mechanical Calculators</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Devices like <strong>Comptometer (1887)</strong> and <strong>Arithmomete=
r</strong> automated arithmetic for businesses and engineering.</p></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>b) Punched Card Systems</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Herman Hollerith (1890)</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Developed a punched card tabulating machine for the U.S. Census.</p></li=
>
<li>
<p>Precursor to IBM machines.</p></li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>c) Analog Computers</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Used <strong>continuous physical quantities</strong> (like voltages or r=
otating wheels) to solve equations.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Examples: differential analyzers for engineering calculations.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-=E2=9C=85KeyPoints">=E2=9C=85 Key P=
oints</h3>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-table-width=3D"760" data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"c0=
1c3bd0-c8e5-4114-b164-afda8a4cfb64" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Period</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Device/Concept</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Contribution</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Prehistoric</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Tally sticks</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Counting &amp; recording</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Ancient</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Abacus</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Arithmetic operations</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>17th c.</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Pascaline, Leibniz=E2=80=99s Engine</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Mechanical addition, multiplication</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>19th c.</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Babbage=E2=80=99s Analytical Engine</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Concept of programmable computer</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Late 19th</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Punched cards (Hollerith)</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Data processing &amp; automation</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<hr>
<p>=F0=9F=92=A1 <strong>Summary:</strong><br>
The <strong>early history of computing</strong> shows a progression from <s=
trong>manual counting</strong> =E2=86=92 <strong>mechanical devices</strong=
> =E2=86=92 <strong>programmable machines</strong>, laying the foundation f=
or <strong>modern electronic computers</strong>.</p>
<hr>
<p>If you want, I can next make a <strong>timeline of computing devices lea=
ding up to electronic computers</strong>, which makes it very easy to remem=
ber for exams. Do you want me to do that?</p>
<p></p>
<ol start=3D"3">
<li>
<p>Computers;</p></li>
</ol>
<p>Here=E2=80=99s a structured introduction to <strong>computers</strong>, =
covering definition, types, and components:</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-1=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3WhatisaComputer?=
">1=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 What is a Computer?</h2>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong><br>
A computer is an <strong>electronic device</strong> that can <strong>accept=
 input, process data according to instructions, store information, and prod=
uce output</strong>.</p>
<p><strong>Key Characteristics:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Speed:</strong> Performs operations much faster than humans.</p>=
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>Accuracy:</strong> High precision in calculations.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Automation:</strong> Can execute instructions automatically.</p>=
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>Storage:</strong> Can store vast amounts of data.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Versatility:</strong> Can perform a variety of tasks (computatio=
n, communication, graphics, etc.).</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-2=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3BasicComponentso=
faComputer">2=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Basic Components of a Computer</h2>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-table-width=3D"760" data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"6d=
fee8d4-49c6-49e8-b225-a8bff19c31b1" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Component</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Function</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Input Devices</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Allow the user to enter data (keyboard, mouse, scanner).</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Output Devices</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Display processed information (monitor, printer, speakers).</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Central Processing Unit (CPU)</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>The =E2=80=9Cbrain=E2=80=9D of the computer; performs arithmetic, logic,=
 and controls other parts.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Memory / Storage</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Temporary (RAM) and permanent (hard drive, SSD) data storage.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Motherboard &amp; Buses</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Connects all components for data and signal transfer.</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-3=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3TypesofComputers=
">3=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Types of Computers</h2>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-table-width=3D"760" data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"58=
9b7555-ca11-4490-93ab-226217443083" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Type</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Description</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Example</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Supercomputer</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Extremely fast, handles complex computations (weather, simulations).</p>=
</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>IBM Summit, Fugaku</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Mainframe</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Large, powerful, multi-user machines for organizations.</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>IBM Z series</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Minicomputer / Midrange</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Medium power, used for departmental tasks.</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>DEC PDP series</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Personal Computer (PC)</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Desktop or laptop for individual use.</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Windows/Mac/Linux PCs</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Workstation</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>High-performance PC for engineering, graphics, scientific tasks.</p></td=
>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>CAD workstations</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Embedded Systems</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Computers integrated into devices for specific control tasks.</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Washing machines, cars, IoT devices</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-4=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3GenerationsofCom=
puters">4=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Generations of Computers</h2>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-table-width=3D"760" data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"25=
2aedc3-a929-423b-87c0-efab064cc8d0" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Generation</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Technology</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Key Features</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>1st (1940=E2=80=931956)</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Vacuum tubes</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Large, expensive, slow, consumed much power</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>2nd (1956=E2=80=931963)</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Transistors</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Smaller, more reliable, less heat</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>3rd (1964=E2=80=931971)</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Integrated Circuits</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>More compact, faster, multi-programming</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>4th (1971=E2=80=93present)</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Microprocessors</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Personal computers, laptops, portable devices</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>5th (Present/Future)</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>AI, Quantum</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Advanced parallel processing, AI, natural language processing</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-5=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3ApplicationsofCo=
mputers">5=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Applications of Computers</h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Business &amp; Finance:</strong> Accounting, online banking, ERP=
 systems</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Education:</strong> E-learning platforms, simulations, virtual l=
abs</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Science &amp; Engineering:</strong> Simulations, modeling, calcu=
lations</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Healthcare:</strong> Diagnostics, medical imaging, patient recor=
ds</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Communication:</strong> Email, social media, video conferencing<=
/p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<p>=F0=9F=92=A1 <strong>Summary:</strong><br>
A computer is <strong>an intelligent machine</strong> capable of processing=
, storing, and retrieving data efficiently. Over time, it has evolved from =
massive vacuum-tube machines to powerful microprocessor-based systems, maki=
ng computing <strong>fast, reliable, and accessible to everyone</strong>.</=
p>
<hr>
<p>If you want, I can next explain <strong>=E2=80=9CComputer Architecture a=
nd how it works internally=E2=80=9D</strong>, which is the natural continua=
tion of this topic. Do you want me to do that?</p>
<p></p>
<ol start=3D"4">
<li>
<p>Major components of a computer; Hardware: processor, memory, I/O devices=
 </p></li>
</ol>
<p>Here=E2=80=99s a <strong>detailed explanation of the major components of=
 a computer</strong>, focusing on <strong>hardware</strong>:</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-1=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3MajorComponentso=
faComputer">1=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Major Components of a Computer</h2>
<p>A computer consists of <strong>hardware</strong> and <strong>software</s=
trong>, but the <strong>hardware</strong> forms the physical backbone. The =
major hardware components are:</p>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p><strong>Processor (CPU)</strong></p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Memory (Primary and Secondary)</strong></p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Input/Output (I/O) Devices</strong></p></li>
</ol>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-2=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3Processor(CPU)">=
2=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Processor (CPU)</h2>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> The Central Processing Unit is the <strong>=
brain of the computer</strong>, responsible for executing instructions and =
controlling other components.</p>
<p><strong>Key Parts of CPU:</strong></p>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-table-width=3D"760" data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"bc=
800dae-8305-43c6-9068-891f5fd2a87d" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Component</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Function</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>ALU (Arithmetic Logic Unit)</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Performs arithmetic (add, subtract, multiply) and logical operations (AN=
D, OR, NOT).</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Control Unit (CU)</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Directs data flow between CPU, memory, and I/O devices; decodes instruct=
ions.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Registers</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Small, high-speed storage for temporary data and instructions.</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<p><strong>Functioning:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Fetch =E2=86=92 Decode =E2=86=92 Execute =E2=86=92 Store (classic <stron=
g>instruction cycle</strong>)</p></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Types of Processors:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Single-core, multi-core, GPUs (for parallel computation), specialized AI=
 processors.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-3=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3Memory">3=EF=B8=
=8F=E2=83=A3 Memory</h2>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> Hardware that stores data and instructions =
temporarily or permanently.</p>
<h3 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-a)PrimaryMemory(Volatile)">a) Prima=
ry Memory (Volatile)</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>RAM (Random Access Memory):</strong> Temporary storage for runni=
ng programs.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Cache Memory:</strong> Small, super-fast memory inside or near C=
PU for frequently used instructions/data.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Registers:</strong> Extremely fast storage inside CPU.</p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-b)SecondaryMemory(Non-volatile)">b)=
 Secondary Memory (Non-volatile)</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Stores data permanently.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Examples: Hard disk drives (HDD), Solid-state drives (SSD), optical disk=
s.</p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-c)Tertiary/BackupStorage">c) Tertia=
ry/Backup Storage</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Magnetic tapes, cloud storage=E2=80=94used for backup and archival.</p><=
/li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-4=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3Input/Output(I/O=
)Devices">4=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Input/Output (I/O) Devices</h2>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> Devices that allow the computer to interact=
 with the external world.</p>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-table-width=3D"760" data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"43=
4f0124-e063-4637-94aa-2f6dbcfd489b" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Type</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Examples</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Function</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Input Devices</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Keyboard, mouse, scanner, microphone</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Allow users to send data/instructions to the computer</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Output Devices</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Monitor, printer, speakers</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Display processed information to the user</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Input/Output Devices</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Touchscreen, network cards, USB devices</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Can send and receive data</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<p><strong>Note:</strong> I/O devices are often classified as <strong>human=
-readable</strong> (keyboard, monitor) or <strong>machine-readable</strong>=
 (sensors, network interfaces).</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-5=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3HowTheyWorkToget=
her">5=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 How They Work Together</h2>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p><strong>Input devices</strong> send data to <strong>CPU</strong> via bus=
es.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>CPU</strong> fetches instructions from <strong>memory</strong>, =
processes data using ALU/CU.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Results</strong> are stored back in memory or sent to <strong>ou=
tput devices</strong>.</p></li>
</ol>
<p>This <strong>flow of data</strong> is the core of every computer operati=
on.</p>
<hr>
<p>=F0=9F=92=A1 <strong>Summary Table</strong></p>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-table-width=3D"760" data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"de=
e2e867-f1a9-4193-b87a-b97eea8b9b39" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Component</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Role</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>CPU</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Processes instructions and manages data flow</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Memory</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Stores instructions and data temporarily (RAM) or permanently (HDD/SSD)<=
/p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>I/O</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Connects the computer with external world for input/output</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<hr>
<p>If you want, I can also explain <strong>=E2=80=9CTypes of memory and the=
ir hierarchy=E2=80=9D</strong>, which goes deeper into how computers manage=
 data efficiently. Do you want me to cover that next?</p>
<p></p>
<ol start=3D"5">
<li>
<p>Software: Operating system, application software</p></li>
</ol>
<p>Here=E2=80=99s a <strong>clear overview of software</strong>, focusing o=
n <strong>operating systems</strong> and <strong>application software</stro=
ng>:</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-1=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3WhatisSoftware?"=
>1=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 What is Software?</h2>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong><br>
Software is a set of <strong>instructions or programs</strong> that tell th=
e computer <strong>how to perform tasks</strong>. Unlike hardware, software=
 is <strong>intangible</strong>.</p>
<p><strong>Types of Software:</strong></p>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p><strong>System Software</strong> =E2=80=93 Manages hardware and provides=
 a platform for applications.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Application Software</strong> =E2=80=93 Performs specific tasks =
for users.</p></li>
</ol>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-2=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3OperatingSystem(=
OS)">2=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Operating System (OS)</h2>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong><br>
The operating system is a <strong>system software</strong> that acts as an =
<strong>interface between the user and the hardware</strong>. It <strong>ma=
nages resources</strong> and provides services for applications.</p>
<p><strong>Key Functions:</strong></p>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-table-width=3D"760" data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"15=
a8c713-3e60-47a5-937b-c88ee1cc6e72" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Function</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Description</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Process Management</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Creates, schedules, and terminates processes.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Memory Management</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Allocates RAM to processes and manages virtual memory.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>File System Management</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Organizes, stores, retrieves, and protects data on storage devices.</p><=
/td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Device Management</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Controls input/output devices using drivers.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>User Interface</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Provides CLI (Command Line Interface) or GUI (Graphical User Interface).=
</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<p><strong>Examples:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Windows, Linux, macOS, Android, iOS</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-3=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3ApplicationSoftw=
are">3=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Application Software</h2>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong><br>
Application software is designed to <strong>perform specific tasks for the =
user</strong>, using the resources managed by the OS.</p>
<p><strong>Categories and Examples:</strong></p>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-table-width=3D"760" data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"a2=
2c911d-ff8c-4470-a043-c4df82951fb5" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Category</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Examples</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Purpose</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Productivity</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>MS Office, Google Docs, Excel</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Word processing, spreadsheets, presentations</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Graphics &amp; Multimedia</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Photoshop, CorelDRAW, VLC</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Image/video editing, media playback</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Web Browsers</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Chrome, Firefox, Edge</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Access internet resources</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Educational</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Duolingo, Khan Academy</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Learning and training</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Enterprise</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>SAP, Oracle ERP</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Business process management</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<p><strong>Key Points:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Application software <strong>requires OS to run</strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Can be <strong>single-purpose</strong> (calculator) or <strong>multi-pur=
pose</strong> (MS Office suite).</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-4=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3RelationshipBetw=
eenOSandApplicationSoftware">4=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Relationship Between OS an=
d Application Software</h2>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">[User] =
=E2=86=92 [Application Software] =E2=86=92 [Operating System] =E2=86=92 [Ha=
rdware]
</pre>
</div>
</div>
<ul>
<li>
<p>The <strong>application software</strong> sends requests to the OS.</p><=
/li>
<li>
<p>The <strong>OS translates</strong> these requests into hardware-level op=
erations.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<p>=F0=9F=92=A1 <strong>Summary Table</strong></p>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-table-width=3D"760" data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"9c=
defeb7-bf00-4d2a-b48d-1078eca9956e" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Aspect</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>OS</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Application Software</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Type</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>System software</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>User-oriented software</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Function</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Manages resources, provides interface</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Performs specific user tasks</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Examples</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Windows, Linux, Android</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>MS Word, Photoshop, Chrome</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<hr>
<p>If you want, I can next explain <strong>=E2=80=9CTypes of Operating Syst=
ems=E2=80=9D</strong> like batch, multitasking, real-time, and distributed =
OS, which is the natural continuation. Do you want me to do that?</p>
<p></p>
<ol start=3D"6">
<li>
<p>Basic architecture of a computer</p></li>
</ol>
<p>Here=E2=80=99s a <strong>concise explanation of the basic architecture o=
f a computer</strong>, covering all essential components and their interact=
ions:</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-1=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3WhatisComputerAr=
chitecture?">1=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 What is Computer Architecture?</h2>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong><br>
Computer architecture refers to the <strong>organization and interconnectio=
n of the hardware components</strong> that define how a computer system fun=
ctions.</p>
<p>It determines how the CPU, memory, and I/O devices <strong>work together=
</strong> to execute instructions efficiently.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-2=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3BasicComponentso=
fComputerArchitecture">2=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Basic Components of Computer Arc=
hitecture</h2>
<h3 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-a)CentralProcessingUnit(CPU)">a) <s=
trong>Central Processing Unit (CPU)</strong></h3>
<p>The CPU is the <strong>brain</strong> of the computer. It executes instr=
uctions and controls all other components.</p>
<p><strong>Main parts:</strong></p>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-table-width=3D"760" data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"05=
7b154b-b0c6-4e51-a4fa-efe355d8c0dc" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Part</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Function</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Arithmetic Logic Unit (ALU)</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Performs arithmetic operations (add, subtract, multiply, divide) and log=
ical operations (AND, OR, NOT).</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Control Unit (CU)</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Fetches, decodes, and executes instructions; manages data flow between C=
PU, memory, and I/O devices.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Registers</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>High-speed storage for temporary data, instructions, and addresses used =
by the CPU.</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-b)Memory">b) <strong>Memory</strong=
></h3>
<p>Stores instructions and data temporarily or permanently.</p>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-table-width=3D"760" data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"4c=
3306d5-20b6-4996-8ac2-ddcb13653164" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Type</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Function</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Primary Memory (RAM, Cache)</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Stores data and instructions currently in use; volatile.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Secondary Memory (HDD, SSD)</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Stores data permanently; non-volatile.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Registers</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Ultra-fast storage inside CPU for immediate operations.</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-c)Input/Output(I/O)Devices">c) <str=
ong>Input/Output (I/O) Devices</strong></h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Input Devices:</strong> Keyboard, mouse, scanner =E2=80=93 send =
data to the CPU.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Output Devices:</strong> Monitor, printer, speakers =E2=80=93 di=
splay results to users.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>I/O Interfaces:</strong> Connect CPU and memory to external devi=
ces.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-d)SystemBus">d) <strong>System Bus<=
/strong></h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> A set of parallel wires connecting CPU, mem=
ory, and I/O devices.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Types of Buses:</strong></p>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p><strong>Data Bus:</strong> Transfers actual data.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Address Bus:</strong> Specifies memory or I/O addresses.</p></li=
>
<li>
<p><strong>Control Bus:</strong> Carries control signals like read/write, i=
nterrupt.</p></li>
</ol></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-3=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3HowItWorks:Instr=
uctionCycle">3=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 How It Works: Instruction Cycle</h2>
<p><strong>Step-by-step process of executing instructions:</strong></p>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p><strong>Fetch:</strong> CU fetches the instruction from memory.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Decode:</strong> CU decodes the instruction to understand requir=
ed operation.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Execute:</strong> ALU performs the operation or CPU accesses I/O=
.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Store/Write Back:</strong> Result is stored back in memory or se=
nt to output.</p></li>
</ol>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-4=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3BlockDiagram(Bas=
icView)">4=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Block Diagram (Basic View)</h2>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">       =
    +----------------------+
           |      CPU             |
           |  +--------+          |
           |  |  ALU   |          |
           |  +--------+          |
           |  |  CU    |          |
           |  +--------+          |
           |  |Registers|         |
           +----------------------+
                     |
        -----------------------------
        |           |               |
    Memory        I/O Devices     System Bus
</pre>
</div>
</div>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-=E2=9C=85KeyPoints.1">=E2=9C=85 Key=
 Points</h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p>CPU, memory, and I/O are <strong>interconnected via buses</strong>.</p><=
/li>
<li>
<p>CPU performs <strong>fetch-decode-execute</strong> cycle repeatedly.</p>=
</li>
<li>
<p>Memory hierarchy (registers =E2=86=92 cache =E2=86=92 RAM =E2=86=92 seco=
ndary storage) balances <strong>speed and capacity</strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>I/O devices allow interaction between <strong>computer and external worl=
d</strong>.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<p>If you want, I can next explain <strong>=E2=80=9CVon Neumann Architectur=
e vs Harvard Architecture=E2=80=9D</strong>, which builds directly on this =
basic architecture. Do you want me to do that?</p>
<p></p>
<ol start=3D"7">
<li>
<p>Basic Information Technology</p></li>
</ol>
<p>Here=E2=80=99s a <strong>comprehensive overview of Basic Information Tec=
hnology (IT)</strong>, covering its core concepts, components, and applicat=
ions:</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-1=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3WhatisInformatio=
nTechnology(IT)?">1=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 What is Information Technology (IT)?<=
/h2>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong><br>
Information Technology is the <strong>use of computers, networks, storage, =
and software to create, process, store, secure, and exchange all forms of e=
lectronic data</strong>.</p>
<p><strong>Key Idea:</strong><br>
IT is not just computers; it includes <strong>hardware, software, networks,=
 and people</strong> involved in information management.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-2=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3CoreComponentsof=
IT">2=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Core Components of IT</h2>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p><strong>Hardware</strong> =E2=80=93 Physical devices used to input, proc=
ess, store, and output data.</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Examples: CPU, RAM, hard drives, keyboards, printers.</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Software</strong> =E2=80=93 Programs and operating systems that =
control hardware and perform tasks.</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>System Software:</strong> OS (Windows, Linux, macOS)</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Application Software:</strong> Word processors, spreadsheets, we=
b browsers</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Networks</strong> =E2=80=93 Systems that connect computers and d=
evices to share information.</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>LAN (Local Area Network), WAN (Wide Area Network), Internet</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Data/Information</strong> =E2=80=93 Raw facts (data) that are pr=
ocessed to produce meaningful <strong>information</strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>People</strong> =E2=80=93 Users, IT professionals, and administr=
ators who design, maintain, and operate IT systems.</p></li>
</ol>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-3=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3FunctionsofInfor=
mationTechnology">3=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Functions of Information Technology</=
h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Data Management:</strong> Collecting, storing, and retrieving in=
formation.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Communication:</strong> Email, video conferencing, and instant m=
essaging.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Automation:</strong> Performing tasks with minimal human interve=
ntion.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Decision Support:</strong> Data analytics and business intellige=
nce help make decisions.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Security:</strong> Protecting systems and data from unauthorized=
 access.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-4=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3ApplicationsofIT=
">4=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Applications of IT</h2>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-table-width=3D"760" data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"2a=
