</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Communication</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Social media, email, VoIP</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-5=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3ImportanceofIT">=
5=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Importance of IT</h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Efficiency:</strong> Faster processing of data and tasks.</p></l=
i>
<li>
<p><strong>Connectivity:</strong> Enables global communication and collabor=
ation.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Accessibility:</strong> Makes information available anytime, any=
where.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Innovation:</strong> Supports new technologies like AI, cloud co=
mputing, and IoT.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Decision-Making:</strong> Improves analysis and business intelli=
gence.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<p>=F0=9F=92=A1 <strong>Key Takeaway:</strong><br>
Information Technology combines <strong>hardware, software, networks, and p=
eople</strong> to manage and process information effectively. It=E2=80=99s =
the backbone of modern business, education, communication, and daily life.<=
/p>
<hr>
<p>If you want, I can next explain <strong>=E2=80=9CTypes of Information Te=
chnology and IT Infrastructure=E2=80=9D</strong>, which goes deeper into th=
e IT ecosystem. Do you want me to cover that?</p>
<p></p>
<ol start=3D"8">
<li>
<p>The Internet</p></li>
</ol>
<p>Here=E2=80=99s a <strong>clear overview of the Internet</strong>, coveri=
ng its definition, history, components, and uses:</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-1=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3WhatistheInterne=
t?">1=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 What is the Internet?</h2>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong><br>
The Internet is a <strong>global network of interconnected computers and se=
rvers</strong> that communicate using a common protocol (TCP/IP) to <strong=
>share information and resources</strong>.</p>
<p><strong>Key Idea:</strong><br>
It=E2=80=99s not a single network but a <strong>network of networks</strong=
>, allowing billions of devices worldwide to connect and exchange data.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-2=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3BriefHistory">2=
=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Brief History</h2>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-table-width=3D"760" data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"2b=
08c680-243a-4088-8724-4ad82904d8b2" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Year</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Milestone</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>1960s</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>ARPANET</strong> =E2=80=93 First packet-switching network by US =
Department of Defense.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>1970s</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>TCP/IP protocol developed</strong> =E2=80=93 standardized commun=
ication across networks.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>1983</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>ARPANET switched to TCP/IP =E2=80=93 Internet=E2=80=99s official birth.<=
/p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>1990</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>World Wide Web (WWW)</strong> invented by Tim Berners-Lee.</p></=
td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>1990s</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Internet became publicly accessible, leading to email, browsers, and web=
sites.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>2000s=E2=80=93present</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Growth of broadband, wireless Internet, cloud computing, social media, I=
oT.</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-3=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3ComponentsoftheI=
nternet">3=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Components of the Internet</h2>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p><strong>Hardware</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Servers, routers, switches, cables, modems, and computers.</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Protocols</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Rules for communication between devices.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>TCP/IP:</strong> Transmission Control Protocol / Internet Protoc=
ol (basic Internet protocol).</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>HTTP/HTTPS:</strong> For web communication.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>FTP, SMTP, POP3, IMAP:</strong> For file transfer and email.</p>=
</li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Services</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Web browsing</strong> (WWW)</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Email</strong> (Gmail, Outlook)</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>File sharing</strong> (FTP, cloud storage)</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Streaming</strong> (YouTube, Netflix)</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Social networking</strong> (Facebook, Twitter)</p></li>
</ul></li>
</ol>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-4=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3HowtheInternetWo=
rks">4=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 How the Internet Works</h2>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>Devices connect to <strong>ISPs (Internet Service Providers)</strong>.</=
p></li>
<li>
<p>Data is divided into <strong>packets</strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Packets travel through <strong>routers and switches</strong> using the f=
astest path.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Packets are reassembled at the <strong>destination</strong> device.</p><=
/li>
<li>
<p>Communication is managed using <strong>IP addresses</strong> and <strong=
>domain names</strong>.</p></li>
</ol>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-5=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3AdvantagesoftheI=
nternet">5=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Advantages of the Internet</h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Communication:</strong> Email, social media, messaging apps.</p>=
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>Information Access:</strong> Search engines, online libraries, t=
utorials.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>E-commerce:</strong> Online shopping, banking, digital payments.=
</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Education:</strong> E-learning platforms, virtual classrooms.</p=
></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Entertainment:</strong> Streaming, online gaming, social media.<=
/p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-6=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3RisksandChalleng=
es">6=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Risks and Challenges</h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Cybersecurity threats: viruses, malware, hacking.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Privacy concerns: data collection, tracking.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Digital divide: not everyone has equal access.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Over-reliance: addiction, misinformation spread.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<p>=F0=9F=92=A1 <strong>Key Takeaway:</strong><br>
The Internet is a <strong>global information and communication network</str=
ong> that has transformed how we live, work, learn, and connect. Understand=
ing its structure, protocols, and services is fundamental to modern IT lite=
racy.</p>
<hr>
<p>If you want, I can next explain <strong>=E2=80=9CWorld Wide Web, website=
s, and web browsers=E2=80=9D</strong>, which is the next step in understand=
ing the Internet ecosystem. Do you want me to do that?</p>
<p>Here=E2=80=99s a <strong>clear explanation of the World Wide Web (WWW), =
websites, and web browsers</strong>:</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-1=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3WhatistheWorldWi=
deWeb(WWW)?">1=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 What is the World Wide Web (WWW)?</h2>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong><br>
The World Wide Web is a <strong>system of interlinked hypertext documents a=
nd resources</strong> accessed via the Internet using web browsers.</p>
<p><strong>Key Points:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Invented by <strong>Tim Berners-Lee</strong> in 1989.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Uses <strong>HTTP/HTTPS protocols</strong> for communication.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Allows users to <strong>view and navigate web pages</strong> through hyp=
erlinks.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-2=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3Websites">2=EF=
=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Websites</h2>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong><br>
A website is a <strong>collection of related web pages</strong> hosted on a=
 server and accessible via a <strong>domain name</strong>.</p>
<p><strong>Components of a Website:</strong></p>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p><strong>Web Pages:</strong> Individual HTML documents.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Domain Name:</strong> Human-readable address (e.g., <a href=3D"h=
ttp://www.example.com/" class=3D"external-link" rel=3D"nofollow">www.exampl=
e.com</a>).</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Web Server:</strong> Stores and serves website content.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Content:</strong> Text, images, videos, forms, links, scripts.</=
p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Navigation:</strong> Menus, links, and buttons to move between p=
ages.</p></li>
</ol>
<p><strong>Types of Websites:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Static Websites:</strong> Fixed content, simple HTML/CSS.</p></l=
i>
<li>
<p><strong>Dynamic Websites:</strong> Content changes based on user interac=
tion (e.g., Facebook, Gmail).</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>E-commerce Websites:</strong> Online shopping and transactions (=
Amazon, eBay).</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Blogs/Portfolios:</strong> Personal or professional content shar=
ing.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-3=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3WebBrowsers">3=
=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Web Browsers</h2>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong><br>
A web browser is a <strong>software application</strong> that allows users =
to <strong>access, retrieve, and display web pages</strong> from the Intern=
et.</p>
<p><strong>How It Works:</strong></p>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>User enters a <strong>URL</strong> or clicks a link.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Browser sends an <strong>HTTP/HTTPS request</strong> to the web server.<=
/p></li>
<li>
<p>Server responds with <strong>HTML, CSS, JavaScript, images</strong>, etc=
.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Browser <strong>renders the page</strong> and displays it to the user.</=
p></li>
</ol>
<p><strong>Popular Web Browsers:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Google Chrome</p></li>
<li>
<p>Mozilla Firefox</p></li>
<li>
<p>Microsoft Edge</p></li>
<li>
<p>Safari</p></li>
<li>
<p>Opera</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-4=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3InteractionBetwe=
enWWW,Website,andBrowser">4=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Interaction Between WWW, Webs=
ite, and Browser</h2>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">[User] =
=E2=86=92 [Web Browser] =E2=86=92 [Internet/HTTP] =E2=86=92 [Web Server] =
=E2=86=92 [Website] =E2=86=92 [Browser renders content]
</pre>
</div>
</div>
<ul>
<li>
<p>The <strong>browser</strong> is the interface between the user and the <=
strong>WWW</strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Websites</strong> are the content stored on <strong>servers</str=
ong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>The <strong>WWW</strong> is the platform connecting servers and browsers=
 via the Internet.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<p>=F0=9F=92=A1 <strong>Key Takeaways:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>WWW</strong> =3D System of interlinked web pages.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Website</strong> =3D Collection of web pages under a domain.</p>=
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>Web Browser</strong> =3D Tool to access and view websites via th=
e <a href=3D"http://www/" class=3D"external-link" rel=3D"nofollow">WWW</a>.=
</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<p>If you want, I can next explain <strong>=E2=80=9CIP addresses, domain na=
mes, and DNS=E2=80=9D</strong>, which explains how web browsers locate webs=
ites on the Internet. Do you want me to cover that?</p>
<ol start=3D"9">
<li>
<p>Number system: binary, octal, hexadecimal, binary arithmetic</p></li>
</ol>
<p>Here=E2=80=99s a <strong>comprehensive guide on Number Systems</strong> =
including binary, octal, hexadecimal, and binary arithmetic:</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-1=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3WhatisaNumberSys=
tem?">1=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 What is a Number System?</h2>
<p>A <strong>number system</strong> is a way to represent numbers using a c=
onsistent set of symbols (digits) and a <strong>base (radix)</strong>.</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Base (radix):</strong> Number of unique digits including zero.</=
p></li>
<li>
<p>Common number systems: Binary (base 2), Octal (base 8), Decimal (base 10=
), Hexadecimal (base 16).</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-2=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3TypesofNumberSys=
tems">2=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Types of Number Systems</h2>
<h3 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-a)Binary(Base2)">a) <strong>Binary =
(Base 2)</strong></h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Digits: 0, 1</p></li>
<li>
<p>Used in <strong>computers</strong> because digital circuits have two sta=
tes (ON/OFF).</p></li>
<li>
<p>Example:</p></li>
</ul>
<p>10112=3D1=C3=9723+0=C3=9722+1=C3=9721+1=C3=9720=3D11101011_2 =3D 1=C3=97=
2^3 + 0=C3=972^2 + 1=C3=972^1 + 1=C3=972^0 =3D 11_{10}</p>
<h3 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-b)Octal(Base8)">b) <strong>Octal (B=
ase 8)</strong></h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Digits: 0, 1, 2, =E2=80=A6, 7</p></li>
<li>
<p>Sometimes used as a <strong>compact representation of binary</strong> (3=
 bits per octal digit).</p></li>
<li>
<p>Example:</p></li>
</ul>
<p>1578=3D1=C3=9782+5=C3=9781+7=C3=9780=3D11110157_8 =3D 1=C3=978^2 + 5=C3=
=978^1 + 7=C3=978^0 =3D 111_{10}</p>
<h3 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-c)Decimal(Base10)">c) <strong>Decim=
al (Base 10)</strong></h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Digits: 0, 1, =E2=80=A6, 9</p></li>
<li>
<p>Standard number system for humans.</p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-d)Hexadecimal(Base16)">d) <strong>H=
exadecimal (Base 16)</strong></h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Digits: 0, 1, =E2=80=A6, 9, A, B, C, D, E, F (A=3D10, =E2=80=A6, F=3D15)=
</p></li>
<li>
<p>Used in <strong>computing and memory addressing</strong> (compact repres=
entation of 4 bits).</p></li>
<li>
<p>Example:</p></li>
</ul>
<p>2F16=3D2=C3=97161+15=C3=97160=3D47102F_{16} =3D 2=C3=9716^1 + 15=C3=9716=
^0 =3D 47_{10}</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-3=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3ConversionBetwee=
nNumberSystems">3=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Conversion Between Number Systems</h2>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p><strong>Decimal =E2=86=92 Binary:</strong> Divide by 2 repeatedly, recor=
d remainders.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Binary =E2=86=92 Decimal:</strong> Multiply each bit by 2n2^n an=
d sum.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Binary =E2=86=94 Octal:</strong> Group binary digits in sets of =
3 (from right).</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Binary =E2=86=94 Hexadecimal:</strong> Group binary digits in se=
ts of 4 (from right).</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Octal/Hex =E2=86=92 Decimal:</strong> Expand using their base po=
wers.</p></li>
</ol>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-4=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3BinaryArithmetic=
">4=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Binary Arithmetic</h2>
<p>Binary arithmetic uses <strong>0 and 1 only</strong>.</p>
<h3 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-a)Addition">a) Addition</h3>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-table-width=3D"760" data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"71=
734464-5e47-46f9-9ce0-60e5d020677b" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>+</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>0</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>1</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>0</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>0</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>1</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>1</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>1</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>10</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>
<p>1012+112=3D10002101_2 + 11_2 =3D 1000_2</p>
<h3 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-b)Subtraction">b) Subtraction</h3>
<p>Use <strong>borrowing</strong> (similar to decimal).</p>
<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>
<p>10102=E2=88=92112=3D11121010_2 - 11_2 =3D 111_2</p>
<h3 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-c)Multiplication">c) Multiplication=
</h3>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-table-width=3D"760" data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"a3=
d20e9a-c2de-4426-87f1-a8d5b86602d1" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>=C3=97</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>0</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>1</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>0</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>0</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>0</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>1</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>0</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>1</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>
<p>1012=C3=97112=3D11112101_2 =C3=97 11_2 =3D 1111_2</p>
<h3 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-d)Division">d) Division</h3>
<p>Use repeated <strong>subtraction and shifting</strong>, similar to decim=
al division.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"IntroductiontoComputerSystems-5=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3KeyTips">5=EF=B8=
=8F=E2=83=A3 Key Tips</h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Binary =E2=86=92 Octal: Group 3 bits =E2=86=92 convert to 0=E2=80=937.</=
p></li>
<li>
<p>Binary =E2=86=92 Hexadecimal: Group 4 bits =E2=86=92 convert to 0=E2=80=
=93F.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Use binary arithmetic for <strong>digital logic and computing circuits</=
strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Hexadecimal is widely used in <strong>memory addresses and programming</=
strong> because it=E2=80=99s compact.</p></li>
</ul>
